    <p class="c6"><span class="c1">Types of Software :</span></p>
    <p class="c6"><span class="c2" style="font-size: 14.5px; font-style:oblique;">Software can be broadly classified into two categories:</span></p>
    <p class="c5"><span class="c4"></span></p>
    <p class="c6"><span class="c7">1. System Software:</span></p>
    <ul class="c8 lst-kix_73enm78wsupk-0 start">
        <li class="c3 li-bullet-0">
            <span class="c2">
                Operating Systems (OS): The most critical type of system software, the OS manages all other programs on a computer.
                Examples include Windows, macOS, Linux, and Android.
            </span>
        </li>
        <li class="c3 li-bullet-0">
            <span class="c2">
                Utility Software: These programs perform maintenance tasks. Examples include antivirus software, disk cleanup tools, and
                backup software.
            </span>
        </li>
        <li class="c3 li-bullet-0">
            <span class="c2">
                Device Drivers: These are specialized programs that allow specific hardware devices to communicate with the computer.
                For example, printer drivers and graphic card drivers.
            </span>
        </li>
    </ul>
    <p class="c5"><span class="c1"></span></p>
    <p class="c6"><span class="c7">2. Application Software:</span></p>
    <ul class="c8 lst-kix_r0f4mw81x6k6-0 start">
        <li class="c3 li-bullet-0">
            <span class="c2">
                General-purpose Applications: These include commonly used programs like word processors (Microsoft Word), spreadsheets
                (Excel), and email clients (Outlook).
            </span>
        </li>
        <li class="c3 li-bullet-0">
            <span class="c2">
                Special-purpose Applications: Designed for specific tasks, such as accounting software (QuickBooks), graphic design
                software (Adobe Photoshop), and project management tools (Trello).
            </span>
        </li>
        <li class="c3 li-bullet-0">
            <span class="c2">
                Web Applications: Software that runs on web browsers, including online banking, social media platforms, and webmail
                (Gmail).
            </span>
        </li>
    </ul>
